ownedComment.body:
This operation creates a new Group Termination Point (GTP). The requesting OS can either specify the list of CTPs comprising the GTP (the list is placed in the tpRefList parameter) or, in the case of contiguous CTPs of the same layerRate, the requesting OS may list the first CTP (in the initialCtpRef parameter) and the number of following CTPs (in the numberOfCtps parameter). The requesting OS may also provide the target OS with the flexibility to decide the list of CTPs by using the gtpEffort parameter. In this flexible mode the target OS uses the tpRefList parameter or the initialCtpRef/ numberOfCtps parameters to determine the total requested bandwidth but it may return a GTP (createdGtp parameter) with a different set of CTPs than those indicated in the original request. Note that this mode allows for the GTP components to be instantiated at a later time by the Managed Element (e.g., upon detection of user's signal). Therefore the operation may successfully return a createdGtp with an empty tpRefList attribute (to be updated at a later time once the component CTPs are created in the Managed Element).
Traceability: R_TMF518_RP_II_0077, R_TMF518_RP_II_0078.

ownedComment.body: This operation can be used to - terminate and map Connection Termination Points (CTPs); refer to UC_TMF518_RP_0037, - unterminate and unmap Connection Termination Points (CTPs);refer to UC_TMF518_RP_0038, - provision Transmission Parameters on a Termination Point; refer to UC_TMF518_RP_0039. The operation is best effort (except where specified otherwise for a particular parameter). The results of the operation are returned so that the requesting OS is aware of what modifications succeeded. If the source TP of a broadcast system is used as input, then the entire multipoint system will be affected based on the new parameter values for the source TP. The tpMappingMode may be set with this operation. When the mode is set to TERMINATED_AND_AVAILABLE_FOR_MAPPING, the target OS will terminate the specified CTP. In this case the target OS must create the specified CTP on the Managed Element if it does not actually exist. Setting the tpMappingMode of an ATM VP or VC CTP can only be done if the CTP has been created. Note that the tpMappingMode can be set only on the ingress and egress CTPs of an ATM SNC since they are the only ones which may not be cross-connected. The provided Transmission Parameter List is a "delta" list that needs to be applied to the specified TP, i.e. only a subset of the parameters may be specified in the list, in which case only those should be applied in the Managed Element. Transmission Parameters are used to associate a TCA profile with a TP using this service. In this case there are potentially additional failure modes (see Use Case). The assignment of a Transmission Descriptor (TMD) to a Termination Point (TP) as egress or ingress TMD by using the TMD's name amounts to an overwriting of the Layered Transmission Parameters of the TP by the Layered Transmission Parameters of the TMD, and to an overwriting of the additionalInfo parameters of the TP by the additionalObjectInformation parameters of the TMD. ownedComment.body:
This operation creates a new Route (e.g. for restoration purposes) and associates it to the given SNC. The route is created in LOCKED state. A route belongs to only one SNC. However CCs/CTPs can be shared by Routes of different SNCs. A route applies to CCs at the same layer of the SNC. The route identifier must be an unique identifier within the SNC name, with format up to target OS. It is possible to specify if the Route to be created is the intended Route or not; if intended, then the former intended Route is updated to backup Route. Only one intended Route can be associated to a SNC at a time. It is possible to specify if the Route to be created is EXCLUSIVE or not; if EXCLUSIVE, then the target OS must find a Route that does not conflict or share CCs with any other existing SNC Route, in any administrative state. Once an exclusive Route has been created by the target OS, any further creation operation which conflicts with the exclusive Route shall be rejected. The Route implicitly inherits the following attributes from its SNC: - the endpoints - owner - direction - rerouteAllowed - networkRouted - connectionRate - type - staticProtectionLevel - protectionEffort is considered EFFORT_SAME, i.e. if target OS can not create a Route with same static protection level as the SNC, the operation is rejected. Note: The relationship between Bundled SNC service and the SNC with Multiple Routes feature requires further study and is not applicable for v3.0.
Traceability: R_TMF518_RP_II_0011, R_TMF518_RP_II_0012, UC_TMF518_RP_0004.

ownedComment.body:
This operation is used to activate the Route provided and deactivate the current (or partial) Route(s), if different from the provided Route. The operation does not affect the administrative state of any Route. The restoration process may re-route again, e.g. in case of failures. In case of failure: No exception thrown, except in the cases listed below. If the SNC or any of its network resources have changed as a result of this operation, then no exception can be thrown so that the SNC state can be passed back to the requesting OS. The resulting SNC state will be either PARTIAL or ACTIVE. The SNC state will be PARTIAL if not all Cross-Connects (of the provided Route) on the Managed Elements have been successfully set up, and there is not an active Route. Moreover one or more of the Cross-Connects to be removed may be still be active, this leads to two (or more) Routes in PARTIAL state. The SNC state will be ACTIVE if all Cross-Connects (of the provided Route) on the Managed Elements have been successfully set up, but one or more of the Cross-Connects (of any of the other partial Routes) to be removed are still active, this leads to one Route in ACTIVE state and another (or more) Route in PARTIAL state. The errorReason parameter is set accordingly. Recovery scenarios: This operation can be performed again addressing - an already active Route, in order to retry the deactivation of other Route(s) in partial state - a partial Route, in order to retry its activation (and retry, if needed, the deactivation of other partial Routes as well). The target OS will apply the Transmission Parameters specified in the tpDataListToModify parameter (same behaviour as setTerminationPointData). They may be applied before or after the creation of the CCs, as appropriate. Existing TP Transmission Parameters for which no changes were requested in tpDataListToModify will be left unchanged. However, the alarm reporting on the CTPs and the containing TPs may be turned on by the target OS as part of this request, unless otherwise specified via the Transmission Parameter "AlarmReporting". A similar behaviour is also allowed for the serviceState parameter, which may be set to IN_SERVICE for the CTPs and the containing TPs. See TransmissionParameters object. If a given entry in the list of Transmission Parameters specified in the TerminationPointData can not be successfully applied to the TP, for any reason, then the errorReason field is appended with an appropriate reason text. Applying Transmission Parameters is best-effort and the resulting values of the Transmission Parameters are provided in the updated tpDataListToModify parameter. An already active SNC Route can be activated again; the target OS is allowed to not send the commands to the Managed Element a second time for the Cross-Connect establishment however the commands may be sent for the Transmission Parameters. Note: The relationship between Bundled SNC service and the SNC with Multiple Routes feature requires further study.
Traceability: R_TMF518_RP_II_0020, R_TMF518_RP_II_0021.

ownedComment.body: The operation verifies the Transmission Descriptor (TMD) state of the specified resource object identified by the resource reference. This operation establishes a point to point Call with zero or more top level Connections across one or more Multi Layer Routing Areas (MLRAs). The operation is atomic; i.e., the Control Plane will either establish the entire Call that matches the parameters requested (including all requested Connections) or will fail the entire Call.
The operation can only be used in a top level MLRA.
At least one end point of the Call has to be within the target OS domain. The other end points may be \"off-network\" TPs (i.e., addressed by a remote address) or an SNP/SNPP/TNA not directly managed by the local target OS.
If routing constraints are specified for the associated Connections, they shall match the constraints based to the degree mandated by the appropriate effort statement.
For more detail on the process of establishing a call in the Control Plane, please see SD1-45_ASONControlPlaneManagement-Primer and SD1-46_ASONControlPlaneManagement-Scenarios.

This operation creates a new route (e.g. for restoration purposes) and associates it to the SNC. The route is created in LOCKED state. A route belongs to only one SNC. However CCs/CTPs can be shared by routes of different SNCs. A route applies to CCs at the same layer of the SNC. The route identifier must be a unique identifier within the SNC name, with format up to target OS. It is possible to specify if the creating route is the intended route or not; if intended, then the former intended route is updated to backup route. Only one intended route can be associated to a SNC at a time. It is possible to specify if the route to be created is exclusive or not; if exclusive, then the target OS must find a route that does not conflict or share CCs with any other existing SNC route, in any administrative state. Once an exclusive route has been created by the target OS, any further creation operation which conflicts with the exclusive route shall be rejected. The route implicitly inherits from its SNC the following attributes: - the endpoints - owner - direction - rerouteAllowed - networkRouted - connectionRate - sncType - staticProtectionLevel - protectionEffort is considered EFFORT_SAME, i.e. if target OS can not create a route with same static protection level as the SNC, the operation is rejected.
Note: The relationship between Bundled SNC service and the SNC with Multiple Routes feature requires further study and is not applicable for v3.0.
Additional information on exceptions: protectionEffortNotMet - Raised when the requesting OS requests a route with a static protection level (inherited from SNC) that cannot be met by the target OS. unableToComply - Raised when the target OS is unable to find an appropriate route. Raised when the target OS can not meet the tolerableImpact requested by the requesting OS. Raised when the target OS is unable to execute the request because at least one of the parameters although valid can not be set and that parameter is identified as "not best effort" in additionalInfo. objectInUse - Raised when the route is in conflict with an \"exclusive\" (even locked) route of another SNC.
Traceability: R_TMF518_RP_II_xxx, UC_TMF518_RP_xxx.

The operation allows an NMS to request the deletion of a route of the subnetwork connection. It is possible to delete a locked backup route which is \"inUseBy\" other routes of other SNCs, because this operation has no side effect on routes of any other SNCs, even if sharing CCs/TPs.
Note: The relationship between Bundled SNC service and the SNC with Multiple Routes feature requires further study and is not applicable for v3.0.
In case of failure: The route will not be deleted on the EMS. The errorReason field of the exception will contain the reason for the failure.
Operation Exceptions: 1. NOT_IMPLEMENTED - Raised when an EMS does not support this operation. 2. INTERNAL_ERROR - Raised in case of non-specific EMS internal failure. 3. INVALID_INPUT - Raised when any input parameter is syntactically incorrect. 4. ENTITY_NOT_FOUND - Raised when routeId reference an object that does not exist. 5. NOT_IN_VALID_STATE - Raised when the route is in the UNLOCKED state, or if the route is the intended one. 6. UNABLE_TO_COMPLY - Raised when the EMS is unable to execute the request because at least one of the parameters although valid can not be set and that parameter is identified as \"not best effort\" in additionalInfo. If the EMS cannot determine the reason it could not comply, it is also allowed to throw UNABLE_TO_COMPLY. 7. NE_COMM_LOSS - Raised when communication to managed element is lost and this prevents the deletion of the route.

ownedComment.body:
The operation is used to activate the input route and deactivate the current (or partial) route(s), if different from input route. The operation does not affect the administrativeState of any route. The restoration process may re-route again, e.g. in case of failures.
In case of failure: No exception thrown, except in the cases listed below. If the SNC or any of its network resources have changed as a result of this operation, then no exception can be thrown so that the sncState can be passed back to the NMS. The resulting sncState will be either PARTIAL or ACTIVE. The sncState will be PARTIAL if not all cross-connects (of given input route) on MEs have been successfully set up, and there is not an active route. Moreover one or more of the cross-connects to be removed may be still be active, this leads to two (or more) routes in PARTIAL state. The sncState will be ACTIVE if all cross-connects (of given input route) on MEs have been successfully set up, but one or more of the cross-connects (of any of the other partial routes) to be removed are still active, this leads to one route in ACTIVE state and another (or more) route in PARTIAL state. The errorReason parameter is set accordingly.
Recovery scenarios: this operation can be performed again addressing - an already active route, in order to retry the deactivation of other route(s) in partial state - a partial route, in order to retry its activation (and retry, if needed, the deactivation of other partial routes as well).
The EMS will apply the transmission parameters specified in the tpsToModify parameter (same behaviour as setTPData). They may be applied before or after the creation of the CCs, as appropriate. Existing TP transmission parameters for which no changes were requested in tpsToModify will be left unchanged. However, the alarm reporting on the CTPs and the containing TPs may be turned on by the EMS as part of this request, unless otherwise specified via the transmission parameter \"AlarmReporting\". A similar behaviour is also allowed for the serviceState parameter, which may be set to IN_SERVICE for the CTPs and the containing TPs. See TransmissionParameters object. If a given entry in the list of transmission parameters specified in the TPData_T can not be successfully applied to the TP, for any reason, then the errorReason field is appended with an appropriate reason text. Applying transmission parameters is best-effort and the resulting values of the transmission parameters are provided in the updated tpsToModify parameter.
An already active SNC route can be activated again; the EMS is allowed to not send the commands to the ME a second time for the cross connect establishment however the commands may be sent for the transmission parameters.
Note: The relationship between Bundled SNC service and the SNC with Multiple Routes feature requires further study and is not applicable for v3.0.
Operation Exceptions: 1. NOT_IMPLEMENTED - Raised when the EMS does not support this operation. 2. INTERNAL_ERROR - Raised in case of non-specific EMS internal failure. 3. INVALID_INPUT - Raised when any input parameter (e.g. tpsToModify) is syntactically incorrect. 4. OBJECT_IN_USE - Raised when the route can not be activated because of CC or CTP conflicts with an active route of another SNC (with equal or higher priority). 5. ENTITY_NOT_FOUND - Raised when routeId or tpsToModify reference a route/TP object that does not exist. 6. NE_COMM_LOSS - Raised when communication to managed element is lost and this prevents any change to the SNC. 7. NOT_IN_VALID_STATE - Raised where the SNC would involve a CTP that is not connectable due to the state of the server TP or in the case of inverse multiplexing where the SNC would involve a CTP that is not connectable due to the state of the client TP. 8. UNABLE_TO_COMPLY - Raised when the EMS can not meet the tolerableImpact requested by the NMS. Raised when the EMS is unable to execute the request because at least one of the parameters although valid can not be set and that parameter is identified as \"not best effort\" in the supporting document SD1-16_LayeredParameters.pdf associated to the TransmissionParameters object or in the additionalInfo attribute; i.e. the whole operation will be rejected if one parameter fails that must be set. This is potentially usable for cases where a parameter must be set for the SNC to be valid. Raised if the route cannot be activated because the EMS cannot comply for a reason different than the ones above. If the EMS cannot determine the reason it could not comply, it is also allowed to throw UNABLE_TO_COMPLY.
